trans-unit.source: !!! The precision of the calculations depends greatly on the accuracy of this value !!! Use advanced options if you have multiple BC's for different velocities.
Used for calculating energy/optimal target weight. Leave default value if not needed
!!! The precision of the calculations depends greatly on the accuracy of this value !!! Avoid using the value on the ammo box as it generally for a 24 inch (61cm) barrel.
Used for calculating the margin of error. Leave default value if not needed
Diameter of the bullet at the thickest segment, very small impact on results accuracy. Leave default value if not needed
Length of the projectile from tip to base, very small impact on results accuracy. Leave default value if not needed

The value of one clicks angle Example: Your scope shifts by 1/10 mrad (0.1 mrad) for every click, set this as 1/10 in fraction mode or 0.1 in default mode. Your scope shifts by 1/4 MOA (0.25 MOA) for every click, set this as 1/4 in fraction mode or 0.25 in default mode

The increment by which the results are rounded. Example: The correction to hit the target is '3.789'. The value of the 'Angular increment' is '0.25' (or 1/4). The displayed value is rounded to '3.75'. This helps the shooter make faster and easier calculations.
The number of 'clicks' to get on target. Recommended for Millirad
The angular correction needed to get on target. Recommended for Millirad/MOA
The angular correction needed to get on target, rounded to nearest increment of your choice. Recommended for MOA
The angular correction as a positive or negative.
The angular correction displayed with L (left) or R(right) as a prefix.
You must enter a value between 0.05 and 1
You must enter a value between 1 and 20
Whether you're a hunter, sports shooter, or military professional, our advanced tools provide precise ballistic calculations.
Our calculator is designed fto supports multiple BC values, allowing for accurate ballistic calculations across various conditions.
To achieve greater accuracy, our calculator includes spin drift corrections, compensating for the effects of rotational forces on your projectile.
Our calculator is powered by JBM's trajectory model. It leverages optimized C# code, extended with insights from Applied Ballistics and Doppler radar data.
